gr.forth.ics.swkm.model2.validation
Class Validator

java.lang.Object
  gr.forth.ics.swkm.model2.validation.Validator
Direct Known Subclasses:
Validator.DefaultValidator
public abstract class Validator
extends Object

A validator has the task of verifying the validity of a Model. This class is abstract since there are various notions of what constitutes validity, or what rules are checked.

defaultValidator() creates a default validator (see the method specification for details).

Author:
Andreou Dimitris, email: jim.andreou (at) gmail (dot) com

defaultValidator

public static Validator defaultValidator()
Returns a default validator instance. Performs these validation checks:
  • Properties must have one domain and one range, without use of inference
  • There are no illegal domains
  • There is no cycle in the rdfs:subClassOf relation
  • There is no cycle in the rdfs:subClassOf relation
  • Each property has compatible domain and range with its super-properties
  • Each property instance has compatible subject and object with the domain and range, respectively, of the property

Returns:
a default Validator instance

checkPropertiesHaveOneDomainAndRange

protected static void checkPropertiesHaveOneDomainAndRange(Model model,
                                                           ValidationHandler handler)
Checks that every property has a single domain and a single range, or in case either is missing, it inherits a single property which does have the missing element (recursively).

If a property has no domain/range, it inherits (by adding the necessary triples to the model, in the default named graph) the domains/ranges of their ancestors. If no domain or range is found, rdfs:Resource is used, and warnings of ErrorCode.NO_DOMAIN and ErrorCode.NO_RANGE are issued. If a property and its ancestors have no domain or range, warnings are issued with ErrorCode.NO_DOMAIN and ErrorCode.NO_RANGE codes respectively, and rdfs:Resource is supplemented as the domain or range of the property.

If this invocation does not report any validation errors, it is guaranteed that properties will have unique domains and ranges afterwards.

If a property has multiple domains or ranges, then errors are issued with ErrorCode.NON_UNIQUE_DOMAIN and ErrorCode.NON_UNIQUE_RANGE respectively.

Parameters:
model - the model to validate
handler - the handler that will receive a warning if this method's check is not satisfied

checkNoCycleInSubClassOf

protected void checkNoCycleInSubClassOf(Model model,
                                        ValidationHandler handler)
Checks that there is no cycle in the rdfs:subClassOf relation.

If such a cycle is found, an error is issued with ErrorCode.CYCLE_IN_SUBCLASSOF code.

Since some validation checks may depend on this hierarchy being acyclic, if this error is found, the rest of the validation process may report redundant problems or not report real ones.

Parameters:
model - the model to validate
handler - the handler that will receive a warning if this method's check is not satisfied

checkSubPropertiesHaveCompatibleDomainsAndRanges

protected void checkSubPropertiesHaveCompatibleDomainsAndRanges(Model model,
                                                                ValidationHandler handler)
Checks that properties have compatible domains and ranges with their super-properties.

If a property is found that has an incompatible domain or range with regards to a super-property of it, an error is issued with ErrorCode.INCOMPATIBLE_DOMAIN or ErrorCode.INCOMPATIBLE_RANGE code respectively.

Depends on properties having single domains and ranges.

checkPropertyInstancesHaveCompatibleTypes

protected static void checkPropertyInstancesHaveCompatibleTypes(Model model,
                                                                ValidationHandler handler)
Checks that property instances have subjects and objects that are "type-of" the actual resources that the property definition declares as domain and range. It ignores properties that are defined in RDF(S), or XML Schema namespaces.

If the subject or an object of a property instance is not a type of the respective domain or range of the property, then an error is issued with ErrorCode.WRONGLY_TYPED_NODE code. There are two exceptions to this rule:

  • if the object is a literal, then:
    • If the literal is typed, then its type must exactly match the range of the property, or else an error is issued with ErrorCode.WRONGLY_TYPED_LITERAL code.
    • if the literal is untyped, then unless the range of the property is rdfs:Literal or an XML type, then an error is issued with ErrorCode.WRONGLY_TYPED_LITERAL code.
  • if the domain or the range of the property if rdfsuite:Class, then exceptionally all metaclasses and metaproperties are allowable as subject or object respectively. In other words, rdfsuite:Class denotes the union of metaclasses and metaproperties.

This check depends on properties having single domains and ranges, and is only reliable when this condition holds.

Parameters:
model - the model to validate
handler - the handler that will receive a warning if this method's check is not satisfied
